{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487214","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487214"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:01:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:01:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"279"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"279","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/279"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.05,0.55,0.02,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"279"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109764"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"279","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/279"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"279"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92163"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"414"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4820"},{"type":"tags","id":"9663"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"926"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2482"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37205"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109764"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for follow-up of her cervical screening test and sexually transmitted infection results. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has two regular male sexual partners and engages in vaginal intercourse only. She has no current symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Nucleic acid amplification testing from her recent cervical screening specimen is positive for \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E. Her cervical screening test is normal and urine pregnancy test is negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate antimicrobial treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Doxycycline","Benzathine penicillin","Ceftriaxone and azithromycin","Erythromycin","Valaciclovir"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has tested positive for \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E infection. \u003Cstrong\u003ECeftriaxone and azithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E in combination is the first-line treatment for uncomplicated gonorrhoea. This dual therapy approach helps prevent the development of antimicrobial resistance. The recommended doses are ceftriaxone 500mg intramuscularly and azithromycin 1g orally as single doses. Combination therapy with azithromycin and ceftriaxone is specifically recommended for asymptomatic gonococcal infection to help delay the emergence of cephalosporin resistance in N. gonorrhoeae\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDoxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E is the first-line treatment for chlamydial infection. While it may be added to the treatment regimen if there is concurrent rectal chlamydial infection, it is not the primary treatment for gonorrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBenzathine penicillin\u003C/strong\u003E is the treatment of choice for syphilis infection. While penicillins were historically used to treat gonorrhoea, widespread resistance means they are no longer recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythromycin\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended for gonorrhoea treatment due to poor efficacy and high rates of resistance. It may be used as an alternative for chlamydial infection in pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EValaciclovir\u003C/strong\u003E is an antiviral medication used to treat herpes simplex virus infections. It has no role in the treatment of bacterial infections like gonorrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing treatment, patients should abstain from sexual activity for seven days and undergo test of cure. Contact tracing of all sexual partners from the previous two months is mandatory, and they should be tested and treated empirically if indicated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["First-line treatment for uncomplicated gonorrhoea is ceftriaxone 500mg IM plus azithromycin 1g PO as a single dose.","Contact tracing of sexual partners from the previous two months is mandatory for gonorrhoea infections.","Test of cure should be performed two weeks after treatment completion."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ong JJ, Bourne C, Dean JA, Ryder N, Cornelisse VJ, Murray S, Kenchington P, Moten A, Gibbs C, Maunsell S, Davis T, Michaels J, Medland NA. Australian sexually transmitted infection (STI) management guidelines for use in primary care, 2022 update. Sexual Health. 2023;20(1):1-8."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92163"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"279"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92163"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-26T10:59:24+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-26T11:00:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"279"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109764"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology"